## D019: Voter & Politician Lens Content — Five CausalChain Render Paths
**Date**: 2026-03-02
**Status**: DECIDED

**Observation**: D017 added voter and politician lenses but left them functionally empty.
The CSS classes `.voter-only` and `.politician-only` existed in lens.css but zero HTML
used them. CausalChain had 3 render paths (educator→accordion, developer→SVG flowchart,
else→step-through); voter and politician fell through to the researcher's catch-all view.
ArticleLayout had educator-only (learning objectives, discussion prompts) and
researcher-only (structured abstract) sections but nothing for voter or politician.
ObservatoryLink hid entirely for both personas.

The default lens (voter) and advocacy target (politician) — the two highest-priority
personas — received the least differentiated experience.

**Methodology**: 2x knock-on analysis at each order + consensus-or-pragmatism discriminator.

**Discriminator results**:

| Decision | Winner | Reasoning |
|----------|--------|-----------|
| 5 explicit CausalChain render paths | Consensus | All lenses deserve differentiation; new views simpler than existing ones |
| Voter: impact narrative view | Both agree | Personal framing needed for default persona; reuses existing data (~55 lines) |
| Politician: executive brief view | Both agree | Staffers need genuinely different view; simplest of all 5 (~45 lines) |
| ArticleLayout: voter .personal-impact section | Both agree | Follows existing educator/researcher pattern; derives from existing props |
| ArticleLayout: politician .policy-summary section | Both agree | Staffers need policy framing; same architecture as educator section |
| ObservatoryLink: no changes | Pragmatism | Keep component's single responsibility; add action CTAs in ArticleLayout instead |

**Decision**: Build five explicit CausalChain render paths + voter/politician
ArticleLayout sections + lens.css display rules.

CausalChain render paths:
- `educator` → accordion (pedagogical, order-by-order) — unchanged
- `developer` → SVG flowchart (technical, interactive) — unchanged
- `voter` → impact narrative (personal framing, 4 summary cards, action CTA) — NEW
- `politician` → executive brief (one-screen policy summary, committee language) — NEW
- `researcher` → step-through (analytical, confidence levels) — moved from catch-all to explicit check

ArticleLayout:
- `.voter-only .personal-impact` — "What This Means for You" + action CTA
- `.politician-only .policy-summary` — Policy brief header (right, status, AI relevance, committee)
- Voter/politician callout CTAs in AI Connection section (action / policy-brief links)

**Reasoning**:
- Voter view: personal-impact framing becomes the default site experience since voter = default lens. 2x knock-on: social sharing spreads personal frame → becomes primary frame for non-technical audiences → compound growth in advocacy volume.
- Politician view: executive brief enables staffers to grasp the case in 2 minutes. 2x knock-on: staffer shares URL internally → site becomes de facto briefing source → increases chance of committee hearing.
- Both new views remain the simplest of all 5 — net complexity increase moderate.
- ObservatoryLink stays unchanged: observatory serves tech/academic audiences, not voter/politician. Action/policy-brief CTAs added as separate elements in ArticleLayout.

**What follows**:
- All five lenses now receive differentiated content across CausalChain + ArticleLayout
- Voter (default lens) sees personal-impact framing + action CTAs throughout
- Politician sees policy framing + committee language + bipartisan alignment throughout
- All new copy written in E-prime with fair witness framing
- ObservatoryLink continues to hide for voter/politician (no architectural change needed)

---

## D020: Visualization Gap Fill — ScoreChart + RadarChart
**Date**: 2026-03-02
**Status**: DECIDED

**Observation**: D013 deferred V5 (bar charts, score 15/25) because "HTML tables serve
the function adequately." Since D013, three changes shifted the calculus:
1. D017 added the five-lens system — voter (default) lens users benefit from visual
   comprehension over tabular scanning
2. Four content pages (differential-diagnosis, ratification-counterfactual,
   dignity-quotient, research-summary) contain 5-10 scored items each in dense tables
3. The dignity-quotient page presents 10-dimension PSQ scoring that naturally maps
   to radar/spider chart visualization

V7 (Sankey) remains impractical — no quantitative flow data exists.

**Decision**: Build two reusable Svelte visualization components and integrate them
across 4 content pages:

1. **ScoreChart.svelte** — horizontal bar chart for scored items (hypothesis scores,
   ratification scenarios, safety net paths). Props: items[], maxScore, title, showStatus.
   Pure SVG, no D3.

2. **RadarChart.svelte** — radar/spider chart for multi-dimensional profiles (DQ PSQ
   dimensions). Props: dimensions[], profiles[], title. Pure trigonometry, no D3.

Integration:
- `/connection/differential-diagnosis` → ScoreChart (7 hypothesis scores)
- `/connection/ratification-counterfactual` → ScoreChart (7 scenario scores)
- `/connection/dignity-quotient` → RadarChart (10 PSQ dimensions, UDHR profile)
- `/evidence/research-summary` → ScoreChart ×2 (surviving hypotheses + safety net paths)

| Design Choice | Rationale |
|---------------|-----------|
| Pure SVG, no D3 | Bars and radar need only `<rect>` and cos/sin — D3 adds zero value |
| Data inline in Astro pages | 5-10 items per chart; co-location keeps maintenance simple |
| Single UDHR radar profile | Only profile with full 10-dimension data; interpolating missing cluster values would violate fair witness |
| `client:visible` | Matches all existing visualization components |
| Theme-aware via MutationObserver | Same pattern as RatificationMap and CausalChain |
| 9 new CSS variables in base.css | Chart colors for both light and dark themes |

**Reasoning**:
- ScoreChart (4.67KB gzipped ~2KB) and RadarChart (5.37KB gzipped ~2.3KB) add minimal bundle weight
- Both components follow every established pattern: CSS variable theming, MutationObserver reactivity, SSR-safe guards, ARIA accessibility, `<details>` text alternatives
- Data co-located in Astro page frontmatter avoids JSON duplication of MDX content
- Fair witness honored: radar chart shows only the UDHR profile (the only one with full 10-dimension data)

**What follows**:
- 6 visualizations now active: RatificationMap, Timeline, CausalChain, Quiz, ScoreChart, RadarChart
- Sankey (V7) remains deferred — requires quantitative flow data that does not exist
- New components reusable for future scoring data (e.g., if additional hypothesis evaluations emerge)
- Bundle profile: ScoreChart and RadarChart each smaller than Timeline (5.97KB)

